  "prompt": "Why don't US representatives run for president?",
  "response": "U.S. Representatives can and do run for president, but there are several reasons why it is less common compared to senators or governors:\n\n1. **Name Recognition and Visibility**:\n   - Representatives often have less national name recognition compared to senators or governors. Senators typically represent entire states, while governors are seen as executive leaders of their states, both of which provide broader platforms and visibility.\n\n2. **Executive Experience**:\n   - Voters and party leaders often prioritize candidates with executive experience, such as governors, who have managed state governments. Representatives are primarily legislators, which some perceive as less directly applicable to the executive demands of the presidency.\n\n3. **Historical Precedent**:\n   - Historically, few Representatives have been elected president. Most presidents have been governors, senators, or vice presidents. This precedent can make it harder for Representatives to gain traction in presidential campaigns.\n\n4. **Time and Resources**:\n   - Running for president requires significant time, energy, and financial resources. Representatives, who must also focus on their re-election campaigns and legislative duties, might find it more challenging to balance these demands compared to senators or governors, who may have more established campaign infrastructures.\n\n5. **Political Strategy**:\n   - Political parties often prefer candidates who they believe have the best chance of winning the presidency. This sometimes leads them to focus on candidates with broader appeal and experience, which can disadvantage Representatives.\n\nThat said, there have been exceptions. For example, James A. Garfield (1881) and John F. Kennedy (1960) were serving in the House when they launched successful presidential campaigns, but such cases are rare. Today, Representatives who run for president often leverage their legislative records, policy expertise, or unique national profiles to build a competitive campaign.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
